page.desc:
My name is Delilah, and I am furry and sweet and the cutest little Rottweiler mix you have ever laid your eyes on. I was pulled out of Gaston County animal shelter at the last minute, I was to be euthanized. My owner ended up in jail, so basically, I did too, but then the rescue came and snatched me up at the last minute and now I am safe.

I have my shots, I am crate trained, I ride really well in the car, and I love to play with all of the other dogs here at the facility. I would love to have a wonderful home and family to call my own though. Please come and adopt me.

page.desc:
She rolls around when she sees you; she cries out for your company, she loves to be cuddled, and she loves to play. Snowball is an ideal companion.

She was one of many cats who were left behind when their owner died during Hurricane Ike. The cats were left to fend for themselves, and they escaped through an open window to find food in the fields behind the house.

Snowball is a doll, a Seal Point Siamese with bright blue eyes and beautiful markings. She's a traditional "applehead" Siamese mix.

To meet this doll baby, click the adoption link on her webpage at www.HappyCatAdoptions.org and fill out an online application. We'll arrange a meeting, and you can cuddle that soft fur and scritch that pretty head.
page.name: Snowball

center.services: Adoptions, TNR, assistance when funds available

page.desc:
It's hard to be an energetic kitten and still be cool! But Tinsel manages with ease. He's a gorgeous boy, with soft, "blue" (dark gray) fur tinged in silver. He loves to flop on your lap, your bed, or on a kitty tower.

Tinsel is one of those pretty boys you knew in high school, and you think, "Wow, I bet he's stuck up," but then you get to know him, and he's a genuinely nice guy--you just can't say a bad thing about Tinsel. He lives in a house full of adult foster cats, and every one of them accepts him. He's just that kind of guy. Okay, sometimes there is a smack on the head or a snarl when that kittenish energy just overflows onto the ancient adult fur!

Where'd he get his name? Well, he and his brother and sisters were abandoned in a carrier by a dumpster with another litter of kittens--Candy Cane and Gingerbread Manny. These poor babies were just weaned and skinny and full of ringworm. How could we turn away? If they were to go to a shelter, they would have been killed.

When we looked at the calendar to see when they'd be ready for adoption, it was going to be right around Christmas! How could we resist?

Would you like to meet this love bug? Would you like to get to know this ambassador of kitten good will?

Go to his webpage on www.HappyCatAdoptions.org and under his photo, click the adoptions link to get to the online application form. Yes, it's long. But it really helps us to make sure we're making a good match.

.

For more information, contact Tinsel's foster dad directly at haroldw1@sbcglobal.net.
page.name: Tinsel Toes

Ahhhh! That's what you'll say when little Silver comes purring up to you with her motor going and her paws waving. She loves to be held, but she loves to play too. And eat. She's a cutey, and just wants a home of her own.

She and her litter mates were abandoned at a local resale shop, and Happy Cat Adoptions stepped in. Silver is one of the most active of the litter, but also loves to be cuddled like a baby and longs for attention.

These cuties are up for pre-adoption and should be ready for delivery Dec. 8. Pre-adoption means you can visit, select your new kitten, pay the fee and fill out the contract, but the adoption is not complete until we deliver the baby after the medical is done. They are old enough to be fixed, so you don't have to wait long!
